column31:
My scholarship journey üá≥üá¨‚Üíüá∫üá∏üá®üá¶üá¨üáßüá©üá™:

2016:

- Graduated BSc Mathematics, UNN (4.65/5.0)
- Decided to study abroad

2017:

- Started NYSC
- Wrote GRE General (308), TOEFL (94), and GRE Maths (Embarrassing score.üòÖ)
- Applied to the US, UK & Canada

2018:

- Got many rejections from Canada
- Got UK admissions, no scholarship
- Got 2 US Admissions for Spring 2019
- Got full tuition US scholarship (Master‚Äôs)
- Finished NYSC
- First visa interview (December 31): Denied

2019:

- Deferred Admission to Fall 2019
- Second visa interview (June 27): Denied
- Lost the admission & scholarship
- Applied to 7 schools in the US, Canada & Germany

2020:

- Got 2 US admissions, other rejections
- Got full tuition US scholarship (Master‚Äôs)
- Started MSc in August 2020 from Nigeria (COVID)
- Third visa interview (December 1): Denied

2021:

- Continued MSc online from Nigeria
- Fourth visa interview (July 26): Approved
- Move to the US in August
- Continued MSc in the US

2022:

- Applied to 5 US schools for a PhD
- Got 3 admissions
- Got 2 fully funded PhD scholarships
- Graduated MS Applied Statistics, BGSU (3.92/4.0)
- Started PhD in KSU (August)

2023:

- Wrote PhD comprehensive exams
- Became the 3rd person ever to pass unconditionally
- Fifth visa interview (July 19): Approved

2024 - Date:

- PhD Dissertation (in progress)

Never give up üéØ

31 Honest Truths Nigerian Graduates Don‚Äôt Like to HearüíÄüçø

1. Your degree alone won‚Äôt get you a job. Skills matter more.

4. Connections often matter more
column31:
31 Honest Truths Nigerian Graduates Don‚Äôt Like to HearüíÄüçø

1. Your degree alone won‚Äôt get you a job. Skills matter more.

2. Nobody owes you employment just because you graduated.

3. NYSC isn‚Äôt a job guarantee‚Äîit‚Äôs just one year of exposure.

4. Connections often matter more than qualifications.

5. Many recruiters don‚Äôt care about your class of degree.

6. Employers prefer experience over certificates.

7. You can‚Äôt rely solely on government jobs‚Äîstart considering other options.

8. Entrepreneurship is not for everyone, but unemployment isn‚Äôt fun either.

9. ‚ÄúNo experience, no job‚Äù is real, internships and volunteering help.

10. Your dream job may not pay well at entry level.

11. JAPA is not as easy as you think‚Äîforeign struggles are real.

12. You may have to accept a job outside your field.

13. Social media can get you hired or fired‚Äîbe careful.

14. Self-employment is not an easy escape‚Äîit requires discipline.

15. Your first salary may barely cover transport and feeding.

16. Learning a high-income skill is more valuable than waiting for jobs.

17. Many job opportunities are hidden‚Äînetworking is key.

18. Your lecturers won‚Äôt help you after graduation‚Äîbuild real-world connections.

19. A Master‚Äôs degree won‚Äôt automatically make you rich.

20. The job market is not fair‚Äîfavouritism and nepotism exist.

21. Soft skills (communication, problem-solving) are often more important than technical skills.

22. Applying for jobs blindly without refining  your CV is a waste of time.

23. Job scams exist‚Äîdon‚Äôt fall for fake recruitment offers.

24. Freelancing can pay more than a 9-5 if done right.

25. Many Nigerian companies pay poorly‚Äînegotiate wisely.

26. If you don‚Äôt keep upgrading your skills, you‚Äôll be stuck.

27. Relocation within Nigeria for better opportunities is sometimes necessary.

28. The first few years after graduation are often filled with struggle.

29. No one will fund your dreams‚Äîyou have to find ways to make money.

30. You must take control of your career because no one else will do it for you.

31. Before investing in anything, have double of that money first.

31. No one gets rich by saving, use your savings for important things that will bring more money

Which one do you think is the hardest pill to swallow?

Woke up to people saying the government started paying 77k because of the NYSC Babes Rant, and it hit me

I‚Äôm existing in the most uninformed era of this country.

A simple search will show that no money can be spent without being appropriated by the National Assembly through a budget. But logic is scarce these days.
Now she‚Äôs ranting about MTN tariffs.

 You want cheap data from a company that lost ‚Ç¶500billion to FX fluctuations in 2023?
It‚Äôs like we‚Äôre being wired to chase low-level conversations and cheap gratification like boat cruises, TikTok gifting, and becoming pseudo-influencers with 2012 GLKs.
Meanwhile, young adults abroad are into quantum mechanics, gene editing, and robot-assisted surgery.
I really hate it here.

Political players sent her death threats. But till today, the videos remain on her page.

One week after all the Raye‚Äôs buzz, FG starts paying the 77k that has been promised since June 2024. Excited Nigerians are saying, if not for Raye‚Äôs outburst, the FG won‚Äôt have paid it.

And even
column31:
NYSC Is Proof Nigeria Is a Land of Opportunities 

The NYSC has fulfilled its promise to pay Youth Service Corp members ‚Ç¶77,000. This is commendable. It is hoped that those who criticised the government should also now acknowledge them. It is only fair to be balanced. 

And even beyond that, let us equally appreciate Nigeria for the scheme, which is a unique way of building your resume, acquiring new skills, and raising seed money before easing your way into the labour market. 

Every Nigerian who graduates from university or polytechnic is guaranteed accommodation, job experience, and a salary for a year through the National Youth Service Corps, courtesy of the Federal Government.

America does not offer such opportunities to Americans. 

Britain does not offer such opportunities to Britons. 

Canada does not offer such opportunities to Canadians. 

South Africa does not offer such opportunities to South Africans. 

Saudi Arabia does not offer such opportunities to Saudi Arabians. 

But Nigeria does. Nigeria also has one of the lowest tuition rates on Earth at its public universities, as well as one of the most funded government scholarship schemes on Earth through the Petroleum Technology Development Fund, Tertiary Education Trust Fund, and the Federal Scholarship Board. 

And as a personal initiative of the President, the Nigerian Education Loan Fund (NELFUND) under Tinubu has given student loans to over 400,000 university graduates. 

But of course, when your eyes are determined to only look for bad things about Nigeria, you will not see these benefits. Your eyes will show you what your mind wants to see because the challenge is your mindset about Nigeria, not necessarily Nigeria. 

Watch other countries. You will notice that they attack their leaders but don't attack their country. They promote their nations. But in Nigeria, we attack our leaders by attacking our country. Leaders come and go, but Nigeria is forever. 

Reno Omokri 

Gospeller. Deep Thinker. #TableShaker. Ruffler of the Feathers of Obidents. #1 Bestselling author of Facts Versus Fiction: The True Story of the Jonathan Years. Hodophile. Hollywood Magazine Humanitarian of the Year, 2019. Business Insider Influencer of the Year 2022. 21st Most Talked About Person in Africa, 2024.

column11: I have offered this advice to many young people in higher institutions seeking to do internship and NYSC over and over. I want to state it again for the benefit of those seeking placements for Industrial Attachment and places of primary assignment during the mandatory youth
column31:
I have offered this advice to many young people in higher institutions seeking to do internship and NYSC over and over. I want to state it again for the benefit of those seeking placements for Industrial Attachment and places of primary assignment during the mandatory youth service. 

Money should never be your consideration when you are seeking a placement for your industrial attachment and NYSC. 

Your first and main consideration should be a place that offers you the best opportunity in your chosen field and career you want to pursue. 

Last week, I saw how a young man who just finished his NYSC dazzled a panel of interviewers of a major oil producing company. His practical real life work experience during his 6 months Industrial Attachment and his just concluded NYSC was top notch. 

The interview session was so deep and technical for almost two hours that I wondered if the panelists forgot they were interviewing a boy who just got out of NYSC barely a month ago. The kind of technical oil and gas industry questions they were asking him would have been perfect for someone with 10-15 years industry experience.

column31:
GENERAL CIRCULAR
IMPORTANT NOTICE TO ALL GRADUATES OF KWASU ON COLLECTION OF NYSC EXEMPTION CERTIFICATE

This is to inform all graduates of the Kwara State University, Malete, who were exempted by the NYSC from service during the 2024 Batch ‚ÄúC‚Äù mobilization exercise that, their NYSC exemption certificates are ready for immediate collection. 

All concerned graduates of the University are enjoined to avail themselves of the opportunity to collect their certificates at the STUDENT AFFAIRS UNIT, Malete between now and 30th June, 2025. Thereafter, all unclaimed NYSC exemption certificates shall be returned to the NYSC Headquarters, Maitama District, Abuja. It then means that, graduates in need of theirs would have to take the risk of travelling to Abuja for the collection.
Please, note that, the concerned graduates are to take along the original and photocopy of their degree certificate or valid statement of Result. You are to also note that there shall be no collection by proxy.

The collection shall be during the official working hours only from Mondays to Wednesdays of the week beginning from 10.00 a.m.

Dr. Kikelomo W. Sallee
Registrar
18th  March, 2025

column31:
Life is unpredictable, and reconnecting with my old primary and secondary schoolmate, Segun, here on Twitter after more than a decade was bittersweet. I was happy to find him, but his story broke me.

During his NYSC year in 2021, he was diagnosed with Mooren Ulcer. Due to financial struggles, he couldn‚Äôt continue treatment and lost his left eye. The pain never stopped, and he relies on expensive eye drops just to cope. He even had to quit his job in 2023 because his vision worsened.

Determined to survive, Segun started a shawarma business, but without a freezer and generator, he couldn‚Äôt sustain it. Eventually, he lost everything, including his home. But he hasn‚Äôt given up.

Now, he just needs a freezer, generator, and air fryer to restart his business and support himself. Let‚Äôs come together for Segun. 

I‚Äôve contributed what I can financially, and I sincerely ask you all to support him too.

Please, if you can help in any way, donations, reposts, or words of encouragement, it would go a long way. 

2003778326
KUDA
Segun Mathew Okubote.
